\noindent {\bfseries\LARGE Italy's Regioni and Province \par}
\bigskip\noindent

Italy’s administrative structure is organized into several layers, with the most prominent being its regioni (regions) and province (provinces). This system reflects the country’s rich historical, cultural, and geographical diversity. At the top of the administrative hierarchy are the 20 regioni, each with a distinct identity and varying degrees of autonomy. Five of these regions—Sicilia, Sardegna, Valle d’Aosta, Trentino-Alto Adige/Südtirol, and Friuli Venezia Giulia—enjoy special autonomous status, granting them greater legislative power, particularly in cultural, linguistic, and economic matters.

Within the regions are over 100 province (or città metropolitane in some urban areas), which serve as intermediate administrative divisions between the regional and municipal levels. The provinces are responsible for local planning, transportation, and some administrative duties. Over the years, reforms have sought to reduce the role of provinces in favor of more direct regional and municipal governance, but they remain a key component of Italy’s territorial organization.

